"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271145922\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is a meniscal tear?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;A meniscal tear is a condition that causes knee pain and other knee symptoms. It happens when a part of the knee joint called the &ldquo;meniscus&rdquo; tears. The meniscus is the cushion of rubbery material (cartilage) between the thigh bone and shin bone (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef77293 \" href=\"UTD.htm?10/21/10578\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ).",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      There are different kinds of meniscal tears, depending on the part of the cartilage that tears and how it tears.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      A meniscal tear can happen suddenly, such as during a sports injury. It can also happen slowly over time. This is more common in older adults.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271145954\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of a meniscal tear?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Symptoms of a meniscal tear can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Knee pain",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Knee swelling (from a collection of fluid around the knee)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        The knee locking, not straightening all the way, or feeling like it &ldquo;catches&rdquo; on something as it straightens",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        The knee giving out, feeling unstable, or feeling like it won&rsquo;t support you",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Knee stiffness",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271145969\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there a test for a meniscal tear?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. Your doctor or nurse will ask about your symptoms and do an exam to check how your knee and leg move.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Your doctor or nurse might order an X-ray of your knee. He or she might also order an imaging test such as an MRI scan. Imaging tests create pictures of the inside of the body.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If your doctor is still unsure whether you have a meniscal tear, he or she might recommend surgery called &ldquo;arthroscopy.&rdquo; This lets the doctor look inside your knee at the meniscus. During arthroscopy, the doctor makes a few small cuts around the knee. Then he or she inserts long, thin tools into the knee joint. One tool has a camera on the end (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef63687 \" href=\"UTD.htm?26/52/27457\">",
"       figure 2",
"      </a>",
"      ). It sends pictures to a TV screen that the doctor sees. If you have a meniscal tear, the doctor can use the tools to treat it.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271146001\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is a meniscal tear treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Treatment depends on how small or large the tear is, your symptoms, and your individual situation.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Treatment for a meniscal tear usually involves:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Resting your knee &ndash; Avoid movements that worsen the pain. Try not to squat, kneel, or run.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Raising your knee above the level of your heart, for example, by propping it up on pillows &ndash; This is helpful only for the first few days after an injury.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Putting ice on your knee &ndash; Put a cold gel pack, bag of ice, or bag of frozen vegetables on the knee every 1 to 2 hours, for 15 minutes each time. Put a thin towel between the ice (or other cold object) and your skin. Use the ice (or other cold object) for at least 6 hours after the injury. Some people find it helpful to ice up to 2 days after the injury.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Using crutches to walk, if you have severe pain",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Wearing a knee brace, if your knee feels unstable",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Taking a pain-relieving medicine, such as",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?19/35/20021?source=see_link\">",
"         acetaminophen",
"        </a>",
"        (sample brand name: Tylenol&reg;) or",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?14/17/14614?source=see_link\">",
"         ibuprofen",
"        </a>",
"        (sample brand names: Advil&reg;, Motrin&reg;)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Doing exercises to strengthen the muscles around your knee &ndash; After your pain improves, your doctor or nurse will show you exercises to do. He or she might also have you work with a physical therapist (exercise expert).",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      In many cases, symptoms improve with this treatment. But if you have a large tear, or your symptoms don&rsquo;t improve, your doctor might recommend surgery. During surgery, the doctor will treat the tear. This might involve removing part or all of your meniscus.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271146016\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How long does a meniscal tear take to heal?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;A meniscal tear can take weeks to heal, depending on the type of tear.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Healing time also depends on the person. Healthy children usually heal much more quickly than older adults or adults with other medical problems.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271146032\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       When should I call my doctor or nurse?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;After treatment, your doctor or nurse will tell you when to call him or her. In general, you should call him or her if:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        You have severe pain, or your pain or swelling gets worse.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You have a fever with knee pain, swelling, and redness.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You have numbness or tingling in the lower leg, foot, or toes.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Your knee locks and you can&rsquo;t get it unlocked.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271146047\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What else should I know?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;People with a meniscal tear have a higher chance of getting a condition called osteoarthritis later on. Osteoarthritis is the most common form of arthritis, which is the general term for inflammation of the joints. Osteoarthritis can cause joint pain, stiffness, and swelling.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H271146062\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       More on this topic",
"      </span>",
"     </p>",
